Both Idea 0 (Structure-Grounded Contrastive Learning, SGCL) and Idea 1 (Dynamic Structural Manifold Regularization, DSMR) address the core problem of length-induced semantic drift in contrastive learning using intra-document structure. However, when evaluating novelty against existing literature, a key distinction emerges.

Idea 0 introduces structural awareness through sampling and loss regularization, which, while effective, aligns conceptually with prior work that uses graph-based regularizations or hierarchical constraints (e.g., Paper 1 on Graph Consistency in DML). The use of structural roles to weight pooling and enforce proximity in embedding space resembles known techniques in metric learning where side information guides similarity. Although applied innovatively to document structure, the underlying mechanisms—structure-informed positive sampling and auxiliary loss terms—are present in the literature, albeit in different domains.

In contrast, Idea 1 proposes a fundamentally more novel approach by modeling the document structure as a *dynamic Riemannian manifold* that actively shapes the geometry of the contrastive learning process. The use of geodesic distances over a learned structural manifold as a replacement for Euclidean/cosine metrics in the contrastive loss is highly original and not reflected in any of the provided papers. Papers 2 and 3 touch on dynamic graphs and motion-based transformations but do not apply such ideas to semantic representation learning or contrastive frameworks. The integration of a feedback loop via a Manifold Drift Monitor and Hierarchical Memory Banks introduces adaptive dynamics that respond to input perturbations—especially length variations—in a way that no current method does. This shifts the paradigm from *using structure as a static guide* to *treating structure as a dynamic geometric scaffold* that co-evolves with the embedding space.

Furthermore, the concept of aligning learning dynamics with discourse-level topology via geodesic-aware losses has not been explored in NLP or contrastive learning contexts. None of the related works combine variational graph modeling, manifold geometry, and contrastive learning in this manner. Thus, DSMR offers a significantly higher degree of novelty and conceptual advancement over both existing literature and Idea 0.

